@TomSweeneyRedHat @giuseppe @mtrmac and I talked about this at the DNF speedup meeting.  As a possible way to increase the build speed of buildah.  

@nalind @TomSweeneyRedHat @mheon @vrothberg PTAL

@rh-atomic-bot r+
@TomSweeneyRedHat these changes just fix and issue where when rpm and APT put down every file they call fsync, which is a rather heavy duty operation, in order to make sure the file gets placed on disk.  That way if the disk crashes, then the files have been written.  In Buildah if anything goes wrong with the disk/system crashing, everything gets thrown away.  So we think this is safe to do.  

This only effects the fuse-overlay file system, if a RUN was using a volume, then the content will get written to disk.
